\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Comprehensive analysis of LaGarNet's real-world performance. \textbf  {(a)} Failure cases in the real world; text colours indicate the source of failure: white for mechanical limitations, blue for assumption oversights, and red for the learning process itself. \textbf  {(b)} Quantitative analysis of failure modes. Note that a step-wise failure does not necessarily cause a trajectory failure; a trajectory is successful if it reaches the success state within 20 steps. ``Messing-near-success state'' is calculated through identifying ``near-success'' steps (NC $\geq $ 0.8 and IoU $\geq $ 0.7) and calculates how often the performance drops in the very next step.\textbf  {(c)} Breakdown of system timing metrics across the perception-action cycle. \textbf  {(d)} Zero-shot generalisation metrics evaluated on an unseen longsleeved dress with soft material properties and high internal friction.}}{15}{figure.caption.15}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:real_world_analysis}{{9}{15}{Comprehensive analysis of LaGarNet's real-world performance. \textbf {(a)} Failure cases in the real world; text colours indicate the source of failure: white for mechanical limitations, blue for assumption oversights, and red for the learning process itself. \textbf {(b)} Quantitative analysis of failure modes. Note that a step-wise failure does not necessarily cause a trajectory failure; a trajectory is successful if it reaches the success state within 20 steps. ``Messing-near-success state'' is calculated through identifying ``near-success'' steps (NC $\geq $ 0.8 and IoU $\geq $ 0.7) and calculates how often the performance drops in the very next step.\textbf {(c)} Breakdown of system timing metrics across the perception-action cycle. \textbf {(d)} Zero-shot generalisation metrics evaluated on an unseen longsleeved dress with soft material properties and high internal friction}{figure.caption.15}{}}
\newlabel{fig:real_world_analysis@cref}{{[figure][9][]9}{[1][14][]15}}
